The whole program is one Python module, emitted in one piece. Every function, every
class, every line of top level setup, in an order where nothing is used before it is
defined. There is one namespace and you are the only one writing in it, so nothing you
define can collide with anything, and nothing you define needs to be imported from
anywhere else in the program.

Return the module as a single fenced python block, and nothing else. No prose around
it, no second block, no JSON, no line numbers, no attribution. You are never asked
which node caused which line. That is measured afterwards, by deleting nodes and
regenerating, and a claim you made about it would only be a claim.

The module must be valid Python. It has to parse. Indentation is four spaces per level
and uniform across the whole file, and it is meaning, not decoration: a function whose
body is indented by one space is a broken program even when every character in it reads
correctly. A module that does not parse is not a program, whatever it looks like.

Put every import at the top of the module, once each.

The tree is the specification, and all of it. Every node is a decision a human made on
purpose, so code that ignores a node answers a program nobody wrote. Emit nothing the
tree does not ask for either: an extra option, an extra parameter, an extra convenience
function is a line no human sentence caused, and it will be found.

Anything that demonstrates or exercises the program goes under
if __name__ == "__main__":, so that importing the module runs nothing.

Emit no comments and no docstrings. The .human tree is the commentary.
